  "summary": "# Weekly Market Briefing \u2014 Week Ending March 16, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 1. Market Overview\n\nBroad indices posted a uniformly negative week. **SPY fell 1.11%** to $669.65 and **QQQ declined 1.03%** to $601.49, while small caps underperformed with **IWM down 1.52%** and **DIA dropping 1.48%**. VTI mirrored SPY at -1.12%. The sell-off was broad-based but relatively orderly \u2014 no single index saw outsized damage. Notably, large-cap tech (QQQ) held up marginally better than the broader market, suggesting some flight to quality within equities.\n\n## 2. Sector Performance\n\n**Winners:**\n- **Energy (XLE: +3.85%)** was the clear standout, with heavy volume (55M shares). Oil majors XOM (+5.90%) and CVX (+5.39%) led the charge \u2014 likely driven by supply concerns or geopolitical risk repricing.\n- **Utilities (XLU: +1.12%)** also posted gains, a classic defensive rotation signal.\n\n**Losers:**\n- **Industrials (XLI: -2.44%)** and **Consumer Discretionary (XLY: -1.98%)** were the worst performers, pointing to growth/economic sensitivity concerns.\n- **Financials (XLF: -1.59%)** weakened alongside rising bond duration risk (TLT: -1.35%), suggesting rate uncertainty is weighing on the group.\n- **Communication Services (XLC: -1.86%)** was dragged down by META's sharp decline.\n\nThe energy/utilities bid paired with discretionary/industrial weakness paints a **defensive, risk-off rotation**.\n\n## 3. Notable Movers\n\n- **META (-4.25%)** saw the largest decline among mega-caps on relatively moderate volume \u2014 worth monitoring for fundamental catalysts.\n- **AVGO (-4.15%)** continued to give back gains; at a 64.1x P/E, any earnings deceleration narrative hits hard.\n- **AAPL (-3.02%)** underperformed tech peers meaningfully.\n- **XOM (+5.90%)** and **CVX (+5.39%)** surged on very high volume, confirming institutional energy accumulation.\n- **CRM (+1.65%)** and **PLTR (+1.12%)** bucked the tech weakness \u2014 enterprise software showing relative resilience.\n- **Crypto rallied broadly:** ETH surged **+11.15%**, XRP +8.95%, BTC +4.77%. This divergence from risk-off equities is noteworthy and may reflect idiosyncratic crypto catalysts (regulatory clarity, ETF flows).\n\n## 4. Key Metrics\n\n- **TSLA's 361x P/E** and **PLTR's 243x P/E** remain extreme outliers vulnerable to any sentiment shift.\n- **Gold (GLD: -3.91%)** and **Silver (SLV: -8.87%)** sold off sharply despite the risk-off equity tone \u2014 potentially driven by margin calls, dollar strength, or unwinding of crowded positioning.\n- **TLT (-1.35%)** falling alongside equities signals neither stocks nor long-duration bonds are providing shelter \u2014 a challenging environment for traditional portfolios.\n- **VZ (P/E 12.6)** and **T (P/E 9.1)** remain among the cheapest names on the watchlist with yields above 4%.\n\n## 5. Themes to Watch\n\n- **Energy momentum** \u2014 is this a short-term squeeze or the beginning of a sustained rotation? Watch crude prices and geopolitical headlines.\n- **Bonds and equities declining together** \u2014 if this persists, it suggests inflation or fiscal concerns are resurfacing. Monitor Treasury auction demand.\n- **Crypto-equity divergence** \u2014 unusual for risk assets to decouple this sharply; watch for potential convergence.\n- **Defensive rotation durability** \u2014 utilities and staples outperforming while industrials and discretionary lag could signal late-cycle positioning.\n- **Mega-cap tech earnings revisions** \u2014 META and AVGO weakness warrants attention heading into Q1 guidance season.\n\n---\n\n*This briefing is for informational purposes only. No investment recommendations are implied.*",
